text.tspan: A-part ~ Am/D Am/D Am/G F/Em | Am/D Am/D Am/G Em/Am
B-part ~ Am Am G G | Am Am Gm Em/Am
Source: KY Contra Tunes and thesession.org/tunes/15717 for the base
Notes: Now this is an interesting number! The B-part follows a pretty standard I/VIIb progression
found in many Celtic tunes, but the A-part uses the "Dorian vamp," pretty unusual in fiddle tunes
but a staple in classic rock. For that reason, I think it's perhaps a more "jammy" tune than a melodic
one; and one version I looked at had a G-F-Em-Am windup that gave it a little more of a bluesy
punch. The top 4 bars are the tune in its base form, and the bottom 4 bars illustrate how I imagine
the tune in a jam setting.
